<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="37" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="37">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="37">
The genus 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Scirtothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scirtothrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scirtothrips</taxonomicName>
currently includes 103 species (
<bibRefCitation pageId="10" pageNumber="37">ThripsWiki 2013</bibRefCitation>
), and two of these have been recorded from Iran (
<bibRefCitation pageId="10" pageNumber="37">Bhatti et al. 2009a</bibRefCitation>
). It includes several important pest species (
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, LA" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of Entomological Research" pageId="14" pageNumber="41" pagination="467 - 479" title="Identfication, distribution, and host-plants of the pest species of Scirtothrips (Thysanoptera: Thripidae)." url="10.1017/S0007485300008488" volume="71" year="1981 b">Mound and Palmer 1981b</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mirab-balou, M" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Insect Science" pageId="14" pageNumber="41" pagination="1 - 7" title="A new species of Scirtothrips infesting Ginkgo biloba in eastern China." url="10.1673/031.012.11701" volume="12" year="2012 b">Mirab-balou et al. 2012b</bibRefCitation>
). The report of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Scirtothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scirtothrips citri" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="citri">Scirtothrips citri</taxonomicName>
(Moulton) from Iran has not been accepted (
<bibRefCitation pageId="10" pageNumber="37">Bhatti and zur Strassen 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
